ngland","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 1020–1067":"circa 1020–1067","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1009–1076":"1009–1076","1040–Male":"1040–Overleden","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Overleden","1000–1032":"1000–1032","1000–Female":"1000–Overleden","before 1015":"vóór 1015","about 1040":"circa 1040","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1032":"1032","About 1048":"circa 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"vóór 1040","about 1020":"circa 1020","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1020–1067":"about 1020–1067","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1009–1076":"1009–1076","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Deceased","1000–1032":"1000–1032","1000–Female":"1000–Deceased","before 1015":"before 1015","about 1040":"about 1040","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1032":"1032","About 1048":"about 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"before 1040","about 1020":"about 1020","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":15,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":46,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard FitzScrope was born about 1020, in France, his father, Scrob The Steward, was 21 and his mother, Fitz Wimarc, was 22. He married Agnes de FitzRichard before 1040, in Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1067, in Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1020–1067":"umbes 1020–1067","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1009–1076":"1009–1076","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Surnud","1000–1032":"1000–1032","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud","before 1015":"enne 1015","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1032":"1032","About 1048":"umbes 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"enne 1040","about 1020":"umbes 1020","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1020–1067":"noin 1020–1067","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1009–1076":"1009–1076","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1045–1100":"1045–1100","1048–Male":"1048–Kuollut","1000–1032":"1000–1032","1000–Female":"1000–Kuollut","before 1015":"ennen vuotta 1015","about 1040":"noin 1040","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1032":"1032","About 1048":"noin 1048","1076":"1076","1020":"1020","1040":"1040","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","1067":"1067","1100":"1100","before 1040":"ennen vuotta 1040","about 1020":"noin 1020","1009":"1009","Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Richards Castle, Herefordshire, England","England":"England","Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England":"Richard's Castle, Shropshire, England","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1020–1067":"environ 1020–1067","1020–1067":"1020–1067","1009–1076":"1009–1076","1040–Male":"1040–Décédé","1045–1100":